Married or not...

257
00:23:28,719 --> 00:23:32,314
...if we don't go after that ship,
it's gonna haunt us the rest of our lives.

258
00:23:32,490 --> 00:23:34,822
I wasted eight years of my life
on this bullshit.

259
00:23:34,992 --> 00:23:37,654
I'm going back to Chicago.
I'm gonna get my Ph. D...

260
00:23:37,828 --> 00:23:41,628
...and I'm going to spend the rest of my life
teaching, reading and writing books.

261
00:23:41,799 --> 00:23:45,064
And somewhere in there I'm gonna meet
an intelligent, successful man...

262
00:23:45,236 --> 00:23:50,173
...who can get through an entire
conversation without using "definitely."

263
00:23:52,109 --> 00:23:56,170
First of all,
I hardly ever say that anymore.

264
00:23:56,747 --> 00:24:00,706
And when are you gonna stop selling
this crap about going back to school?

265
00:24:00,885 --> 00:24:04,218
You want history?
It's under the ocean, lady.

266
00:24:05,423 --> 00:24:08,688
What, are you telling me you wanna
spend your life in some dark room...

267
00:24:08,859 --> 00:24:11,259
...taking notes and writing books...

268
00:24:11,429 --> 00:24:14,592
...about what some old putz in
another room cooked up in his head...

269
00:24:14,765 --> 00:24:17,199
...about things
that you have actually seen...

270
00:24:17,368 --> 00:24:21,134
...and touched and pulled out of the sand
with your own hands?

271
00:24:24,240 --> 00:24:26,037
Bullshit.

272
00:24:28,578 --> 00:24:31,274
I'm so glad we're not married anymore.

273
00:24:37,454 --> 00:24:40,787
Well, where are you gonna get
the tuition money anyway?

274
00:24:40,957 --> 00:24:44,120
That's the best part. By selling the boat.

275
00:24:45,094 --> 00:24:48,359
By selling my boat, which belongs to me,
which used to belong to us...

276
00:24:48,531 --> 00:24:50,999
...but you missed the divorce
so now it belongs to me.

277
00:24:51,568 --> 00:24:54,628
I'm gonna fix it up, I'm gonna sell it,
and I'm going back... What?

278
00:24:54,804 --> 00:24:55,930
This is hard to say.

279
00:24:56,105 --> 00:24:57,732
What is?

280
00:25:15,692 --> 00:25:18,217
Well, you act like this is totally my fault.

281
00:25:19,162 --> 00:25:21,892
Can I borrow this cane
for a second, please?

282
00:25:22,065 --> 00:25:23,794
Oh, come on, Tess.
You're not gonna hit me.

283
00:25:23,967 --> 00:25:25,229
Ugh.

284
00:25:29,037 --> 00:25:30,664
Sorry.

285
00:26:02,938 --> 00:26:04,803
Oh, my God.

286
00:26:06,508 --> 00:26:08,169
Oh, my God.

287
00:26:09,411 --> 00:26:10,810
Oh, God.

288
00:26:39,373 --> 00:26:41,898
I take it they didn't kill you.

289
00:26:45,913 --> 00:26:47,278
No...

290
00:26:47,848 --> 00:26:49,577
...but thanks for your help.

291
00:26:50,217 --> 00:26:52,617
- You need help.
- You are not my mother.

292
00:26:52,787 --> 00:26:53,811
You're right.

293
00:26:53,988 --> 00:26:57,424
I guess maybe I act like your mother
sometimes because I never had one.

294
00:26:57,592 --> 00:26:58,650
Easy, Gary, easy.

295
00:26:58,826 --> 00:27:01,761
Okay, look, the main thing is
we get away from Key West.

296
00:27:01,929 --> 00:27:05,763
The second Finn lays eyes on this boat,
he's gonna be on board in 10 minutes.

297
00:27:05,933 --> 00:27:08,367
What do you mean?
You told him you're working here?

298
00:27:08,536 --> 00:27:10,766
- Are you kidding?
- Then I don't get it.

299
00:27:11,339 --> 00:27:13,432
He needs money, Gary.

300
00:27:13,641 --> 00:27:16,576
Another boat, new equipment, everything.

301
00:27:16,744 --> 00:27:19,975
And I doubt he's gonna squeeze
another dime out of that Bugs Bunny.

302
00:27:20,147 --> 00:27:23,344
- Bugs Bunny?
- The rapper guy we had the fight about.

303
00:27:23,517 --> 00:27:25,314
- You mean Bigg Bunny Deenz?
- Yeah.

304
00:27:25,486 --> 00:27:28,284
- Bigg Bunny Deenz is Finn's investor?
- Yeah.

305
00:27:28,456 --> 00:27:31,550
- Hey, Gary?
- He is a very dangerous guy.

306
00:27:31,726 --> 00:27:34,092
I did like that one song he had,
"Call Me Thumper."

307
00:27:34,261 --> 00:27:35,455
That was some funny shit.

308
00:27:35,630 --> 00:27:37,928
- Anyway...
- There's something wrong with my bisque.

309
00:27:38,098 --> 00:27:39,497
- I'm sorry, honey.
- Anyway...

310
00:27:39,666 --> 00:27:42,396
But I don't get it,
because has Finn ever even met Nigel?

311
00:27:42,569 --> 00:27:45,231
No. But he will, don't you understand?

312
00:27:45,405 --> 00:27:48,101
He is a genius at exactly three things:

313
00:27:48,274 --> 00:27:53,712
Treasure salving, finding money
for treasure salving, and one other thing.

314
00:27:55,682 --> 00:27:57,616
- What other thing?
- What other thing?

315
00:27:59,352 --> 00:28:01,013
I don't wanna talk about it.

316
00:28:01,187 --> 00:28:03,314
How do you plan to get another boat?

317
00:28:03,490 --> 00:28:06,755
I can't think about this right now, Alfonz.

318
00:28:07,927 --> 00:28:09,360
I just got divorced.

319
00:28:10,530 --> 00:28:12,725
May I make a suggestion?

320
00:28:13,867 --> 00:28:15,266
No.

321
00:28:16,703 --> 00:28:19,001
You see that big yacht lying offshore?

322
00:28:19,639 --> 00:28:20,663
No, which one?

323
00:28:20,840 --> 00:28:23,673
The owner is Nigel Honeycutt.

324
00:28:24,978 --> 00:28:26,570
- So what?
- I only mention it...

325
00:28:26,746 --> 00:28:32,082
...because he is worth $ 700 million.

326
00:28:34,220 --> 00:28:37,917
And just to let you know,
I'm back on board, obviously.

327
00:28:38,324 --> 00:28:40,884
So whenever you want to weigh anchor
is great.

328
00:28:41,661 --> 00:28:43,127
Thank you.

329
00:28:43,796 --> 00:28:45,661
So should I tell the captain?

330
00:28:45,831 --> 00:28:47,958
Ready to weigh anchor?
Ready to push off?

331
00:28:49,068 --> 00:28:50,797
Actually, no.

332
00:28:50,969 --> 00:28:54,097
My daughter, Gemma, is joining us today...

333
00:28:54,273 --> 00:28:56,264
...and I said I would wait here for her.

334
00:28:56,442 --> 00:28:58,910
Oh, great. God.

335
00:28:59,812 --> 00:29:01,905
When is she coming?
Where is she coming from?

336
00:29:02,081 --> 00:29:04,106
How far away is she? How great.

337
00:29:04,516 --> 00:29:06,677
I sent the chopper to Miami...

338
00:29:07,319 --> 00:29:09,787
...but she could be anywhere.

339
00:29:09,955 --> 00:29:13,447
That's so funny that you would wait
in Key West for her...

340
00:29:13,625 --> 00:29:16,355
...when she's coming by chopper.

341
00:29:16,528 --> 00:29:18,587
- Is it?
- Well, just because the helicopter...

342
00:29:18,764 --> 00:29:20,493
...could just meet the boat anywhere.

343
00:29:20,666 --> 00:29:24,898
I mean, anywhere at all, that's what's
so incredibly great about helicopters.

344
00:29:25,904 --> 00:29:28,429
She wants to do some shopping.

345
00:29:35,247 --> 00:29:36,737
What do you do, Tess?

346
00:29:38,917 --> 00:29:41,317
I'm the new steward.

347
00:29:42,521 --> 00:29:44,318
But what do you really do?

348
00:29:44,490 --> 00:29:48,755
What makes you think I do anything
besides stewarding?

349
00:29:48,926 --> 00:29:53,124
Stewing, stewarding,
stewarding? Stewarding.

350
00:29:53,297 --> 00:29:57,996
My infallible lifelong instinct
for sizing people up.

351
00:30:00,738 --> 00:30:02,103
Have you sized me up?

352
00:30:03,274 --> 00:30:04,866
Not quite.

353
00:30:06,444 --> 00:30:10,608
You don't mind the work,
but you're not here for long.

354
00:30:11,115 --> 00:30:16,280
You have a deep but not entirely unclouded
love for the sea.

355
00:30:17,288 --> 00:30:20,416
You perform your duties
with superlative efficiency and ease...

356
00:30:20,591 --> 00:30:23,389
...suggestive of someone expending
approximately one-tenth...

357
00:30:23,561 --> 00:30:25,426
...of her available brain power.

358
00:30:26,731 --> 00:30:28,164
So...

359
00:30:28,966 --> 00:30:31,730
...what do you do
with the remaining 90 percent...

360
00:30:31,903 --> 00:30:33,837
...when you're not getting divorced?

361
00:30:37,441 --> 00:30:39,671
I hope I'm not being too personal.

362
00:30:42,513 --> 00:30:46,347
No, not at... Not at all.

363
00:30:50,121 --> 00:30:53,647
It's just been a crazy couple of years.

364
00:30:57,761 --> 00:30:59,160
It's probably his helicopter.

365
00:30:59,329 --> 00:31:01,456
His daughter
is supposed to be arriving today.

366
00:31:01,631 --> 00:31:04,361
The whole town is buzzing
with excitement.

367
00:31:22,886 --> 00:31:26,720
Hey, so where you say
this, uh, museum is at?

368
00:31:28,391 --> 00:31:30,621
Number 2, Water Street.

369
00:31:30,794 --> 00:31:34,321
Okay, uh, every street on this island
is called Water Street.

370
00:31:34,497 --> 00:31:37,227
This place has a magic atmosphere.

371
00:31:37,400 --> 00:31:39,368
Will you just find
the damn address, man?

372
00:31:39,536 --> 00:31:42,061
Yo, Cordell, we got MapQuest
on these things?

373
00:32:24,246 --> 00:32:26,612
- Hi, Daddy.
- Hello, darling.

374
00:32:29,218 --> 00:32:31,118
Hello, my baby.

375
00:32:31,287 --> 00:32:32,982
Daddy.

376
00:32:38,394 --> 00:32:41,158
- Pleasant flight?
- Uh-huh.

377
00:32:42,231 --> 00:32:45,098
So, um, is this the whole boat?

378
00:32:46,835 --> 00:32:50,498
- Yes.
- Oh, so cute.

379
00:32:50,673 --> 00:32:53,005
I can't believe we're at sea.

380
00:32:53,175 --> 00:32:56,338
Well, uh, technically, we're at anchor.

381
00:32:56,512 --> 00:33:02,450
Oh, wait, okay. So that just means
that the anchor is in the water, right?

382
00:33:03,351 --> 00:33:04,648
- Yes.
- Yes.

383
00:33:04,819 --> 00:33:08,220
Okay. Because I totally wanna learn
all the sea terms.

384
00:33:08,389 --> 00:33:10,220
And so you shall, my darling.

385
00:33:10,391 --> 00:33:13,622
Okay, let me try again.
Excuse me, Nigel.

386
00:33:13,795 --> 00:33:16,161
Yes, my dear.

387
00:33:16,831 --> 00:33:18,890
You know what,
let's not do the accent thing.

388
00:33:19,100 --> 00:33:20,624
It's no good?

389
00:33:22,337 --> 00:33:24,100
It's fine.

390
00:33:24,372 --> 00:33:26,499
Um... Anyway...

391
00:33:26,674 --> 00:33:31,509
Nigel, remember when you asked me
this afternoon what I really did?

392
00:33:45,893 --> 00:33:47,190
Have fun shopping.

393
00:33:47,362 --> 00:33:48,989
Thank you, Daddy.

394
00:33:49,163 --> 00:33:51,631
Do try to keep it
under 50 thousand.

395
00:33:52,433 --> 00:33:53,457
What? Ha.

396
00:33:55,269 --> 00:33:56,463
Supper's at 7.

397
00:33:56,637 --> 00:34:00,334
I was supposed to meet some friends,
but I'm gonna try to get out of it.

398
00:34:00,508 --> 00:34:02,772
Invite them aboard if you like.
Just let me know.

399
00:34:02,944 --> 00:34:04,969
Okay, I will. Love you.

400
00:34:24,331 --> 00:34:25,662
My hat.

401
00:34:33,940 --> 00:34:36,841
Hey, look. The hat, he is a Frisbee.

402
00:34:37,010 --> 00:34:39,171
Can you turn the boat around?
Thank you.

403
00:34:39,346 --> 00:34:41,974
Okay, but we never gonna catch him.

404
00:35:06,273 --> 00:35:07,570
Whoa!

405
00:35:10,744 --> 00:35:11,767
God.

406
00:35:15,915 --> 00:35:17,382
- Oh, shit.
- Oh.

407
00:35:19,285 --> 00:35:22,413
Oh, my God. You killed him.

408
00:35:23,255 --> 00:35:25,450
Ow. Ow. Ow.

409
00:35:30,629 --> 00:35:32,256
What in God's name happened?

410
00:35:32,865 --> 00:35:35,891
Daddy, this man saved my life.

411
00:35:36,068 --> 00:35:37,729
Sir, sir...

412
00:35:38,170 --> 00:35:41,264
...I really don't think you should get up
until I make sure...

413
00:35:51,283 --> 00:35:53,444
Is this your hat?

414
00:35:54,120 --> 00:35:55,280
Yes. Ha-ha.

415
00:35:56,489 --> 00:36:02,086
That was the bravest thing
I've ever seen in my life.

416
00:36:03,596 --> 00:36:07,930
Sir, thank you so much.

417
00:36:08,100 --> 00:36:09,124
Thank you.

418
00:36:09,301 --> 00:36:10,996
- Thank you, indeed.
- He'll be okay.

419
00:36:11,170 --> 00:36:13,070
Just a little bump on the head.

420
00:36:13,239 --> 00:36:16,799
Just try not to move around too much
for the next few hours.

421
00:36:17,509 --> 00:36:21,639
- But I gotta go back to town.
- Oh, I really don't advise it.

422
00:36:22,013 --> 00:36:23,207
Oh...

423
00:36:23,448 --> 00:36:24,745
Now what am I gonna do?

424
00:36:25,617 --> 00:36:26,709
Uh...

425
00:36:26,885 --> 00:36:31,117
May I suggest a hot shower,
some clean clothes...

426
00:36:31,289 --> 00:36:32,586
...and cocktails at 6:30?

427
00:36:33,191 --> 00:36:36,354
Okay. Thanks.

428
00:36:37,629 --> 00:36:40,029
Take him to the Saint Regis.

429
00:36:41,799 --> 00:36:46,293
Whoa, whoa.
Yep, yep, yep, I'm good. I'm good.

430
00:36:47,639 --> 00:36:49,197
Hey, Mr. Honeycutt?

431
00:36:49,374 --> 00:36:53,037
Miss Honeycutt,
she leave him on the boat.

432
00:36:53,211 --> 00:36:56,840
Gemma. Your lifeline
to civilization, darling.

433
00:36:59,517 --> 00:37:01,075
Oh.

434
00:37:01,386 --> 00:37:04,287
Oh, my God, I would have been so dead.

435
00:37:04,455 --> 00:37:06,423
Here you are, darling.

436
00:37:14,098 --> 00:37:18,558
Well, Mr. Deenz, I'm always delighted
to welcome an entrant into my field...

437
00:37:18,736 --> 00:37:21,067
...whether it be on land or sea.

438
00:37:21,638 --> 00:37:24,402
But I feel I need to warn you.

439
00:37:24,708 --> 00:37:26,835
There's no way
of getting away from treasure...

440
00:37:27,010 --> 00:37:29,672
...once it's fastened itself on your mind.

441
00:37:29,846 --> 00:37:32,337
I want you to find me the Queen's Dowry.

442
00:37:32,516 --> 00:37:33,847
Heh.

443
00:37:34,017 --> 00:37:37,885
- Well, now, Bunny, uh...
- Bigg Bunny. It's one word.

444
00:37:40,390 --> 00:37:43,018
Well, that's an emerald
of a different color, isn't it?

445
00:37:43,694 --> 00:37:45,321
Cordell.

446
00:37:52,069 --> 00:37:55,800
This is a piece of the plate
that we found in the Bahamas...

447
00:37:55,973 --> 00:37:59,773
...off of Topsail Cay.
Now, if you turn it over...

448
00:37:59,943 --> 00:38:03,401
...you may notice that it has
the Vangor family crest stamped on it.

449
00:38:03,580 --> 00:38:05,514
That's what that is right there.

450
00:38:07,251 --> 00:38:08,513
That's very nice, uh...

451
00:38:10,454 --> 00:38:12,547
...but who the hell are the Vangors...

452
00:38:12,723 --> 00:38:16,557
...and why the hell should I give
a rat's ass about their family crest?

453
00:38:21,632 --> 00:38:25,398
It's not an investment, per se,
because you probably won't see a dime...

454
00:38:25,569 --> 00:38:28,366
...but it's a chance to pull out
a piece of living history...

455
00:38:28,537 --> 00:38:31,370
...from the sand
with your own two hands.

456
00:38:34,644 --> 00:38:35,804
<i>To the Aurelia.</i>

457
00:38:39,282 --> 00:38:40,749
Hey, babe.

458
00:38:41,450 --> 00:38:42,678
What are you doing here?

459
00:38:42,852 --> 00:38:44,444
Have a good dinner.

460
00:38:45,988 --> 00:38:48,047
<i>Bon appétit, everybody.</i>

461
00:38:49,258 --> 00:38:50,282
Ugh!

462
00:38:54,997 --> 00:38:56,726
I take it you've met.

463
00:38:57,199 --> 00:39:02,330
So Tess and I first hooked up when
we worked for this cat named Moe Fitch.

464
00:39:02,505 --> 00:39:06,271
He's kind of a local character, you know,
big talker, lot of tall tales...

465
00:39:06,442 --> 00:39:07,841
...a lovable, old sea dog.

466
00:39:08,010 --> 00:39:11,673
- You should live to be so eccentric.
- Ooh...

467
00:39:11,847 --> 00:39:13,246
Thank you, babe.

468
00:39:13,416 --> 00:39:15,316
I do wish you would sit down.

469
00:39:15,918 --> 00:39:19,581
Moe Fitch is the most respected and
successful treasure salver in the world.

470
00:39:19,755 --> 00:39:21,814
- Nobody said he wasn't.
- When Finn met Moe...

471
00:39:21,991 --> 00:39:24,186
...he was repairing outboards
and lawn mowers...

472
00:39:24,360 --> 00:39:26,828
...during the brief intervals
he wasn't getting fired.

473
00:39:26,996 --> 00:39:28,896
Two times, Tess. I got fired two times.

474
00:39:29,065 --> 00:39:30,929
I'll be off in one second.

475
00:39:31,366 --> 00:39:34,301
Moe picked him out of a puddle
of motor oil and suntan lotion...

476
00:39:34,469 --> 00:39:38,701
...gave him a job, a vocation,
taught him everything he knows.

477
00:39:40,875 --> 00:39:42,570
Almost.

478
00:39:44,079 --> 00:39:47,515
Anyway, then they had a tremendous
falling-out over this cannon we found...

479
00:39:47,682 --> 00:39:49,445
On our day off.

480
00:39:49,617 --> 00:39:52,711
<i>From the Aurelia,
three miles east of Vero Beach.</i>

481
00:39:52,887 --> 00:39:56,414
Which the court ruled was Moe's,
because we borrowed his equipment.

482
00:39:58,193 --> 00:40:00,661
The sea is all attached, right?

483
00:40:00,995 --> 00:40:02,826
To what, darling?

484
00:40:02,997 --> 00:40:05,557
Kerry and Vivante
grabbed a plane for the Yucatân...

485
00:40:05,734 --> 00:40:07,964
...and I thought
we could hook up with them...

486
00:40:08,136 --> 00:40:11,003
...instead of just sailing around
doing nothing.

487
00:40:13,108 --> 00:40:15,042
Tell us about the treasure.

488
00:40:21,483 --> 00:40:24,975
July 31 st, 1715.

489
00:40:25,153 --> 00:40:28,919
A hurricane sinks the entire Spanish
treasure fleet off the coast of Florida...

490
00:40:29,090 --> 00:40:31,581
<i>...including her flagship, the Capitana...</i>

491
00:40:31,760 --> 00:40:35,855
...which, according to its manifest,
carried the Queen's Dowry.

492
00:40:36,029 --> 00:40:39,396
Forty chests
of jewelry and gold crowns...

493
00:40:39,566 --> 00:40:42,592
...especially crafted in the Orient
for the new queen of Spain.

494
00:40:42,770 --> 00:40:45,238
When we say jewels, we mean...

495
00:40:45,406 --> 00:40:51,311
...Indian diamonds, Burmese rubies and
Colombian emeralds the size of your fist.

496
00:40:51,478 --> 00:40:55,312
We should probably start with what Tess
and I got excited about on our honeymoon.

497
00:40:55,482 --> 00:40:57,541
Well, I think we can all guess.

498
00:40:59,553 --> 00:41:01,578
After we lost the court case...

499
00:41:01,755 --> 00:41:04,485
...we decided to go backpacking in Spain
for two weeks.

500
