It's a totality of his emotional commitment
to the task at hand.

740
00:56:53,391 --> 00:56:55,325
Yeah, it's the focus. It's the focus.

741
00:56:55,493 --> 00:56:57,358
He sees it. He wants it.

742
00:56:57,829 --> 00:57:01,196
- He goes after it. He gets it.
- He sure got me.

743
00:57:01,366 --> 00:57:02,890
Do you mind?

744
00:57:03,968 --> 00:57:06,095
- I'm sorry.
- We're sorry.

745
00:57:11,576 --> 00:57:12,873
Well...

746
00:57:13,044 --> 00:57:17,174
Here's to a wonderfully exciting first day...

747
00:57:17,348 --> 00:57:21,307
...and to the safe landing
of our glorious leader.

748
00:57:22,153 --> 00:57:26,180
Hear, says I. Hear, hear, Nigel.
You the man.

749
00:57:27,859 --> 00:57:29,417
No, he meant you, stupid.

750
00:57:30,094 --> 00:57:31,118
What?

751
00:57:31,295 --> 00:57:33,763
- No, Finn, honey, Finn.
- Oh.

752
00:57:33,931 --> 00:57:36,832
There's port in the salon
if anyone's interested...

753
00:57:37,001 --> 00:57:38,901
...and a wonderful selection of cigars...

754
00:57:39,070 --> 00:57:42,528
...if anyone feels like
ruining the evening for the rest of us...

755
00:57:42,707 --> 00:57:44,004
...and cupcakes.

756
00:57:44,175 --> 00:57:45,733
Are there any prostitutes?

757
00:57:48,646 --> 00:57:50,841
Sorry. No.

758
00:57:51,015 --> 00:57:52,709
Well, maybe we can call some.

759
00:57:53,817 --> 00:57:55,751
Oh. My God, are you serious?

760
00:57:56,753 --> 00:57:59,551
Pay him no attention, Gemma,
he's a provocateur.

761
00:57:59,723 --> 00:58:03,454
Okay, but we're not in France right now,
we're in America.

762
00:58:07,597 --> 00:58:10,157
- Think I'm gonna head to bed.
- That's it for me tonight.

763
00:58:12,369 --> 00:58:15,566
A coincidence that we got up together,
and we're both going to bed...

764
00:58:15,739 --> 00:58:18,401
...because we're not going
to bed together.

765
00:58:18,575 --> 00:58:19,599
- Obviously.
- No.

766
00:58:19,776 --> 00:58:21,971
Well, it's really none of our business.

767
00:58:22,145 --> 00:58:24,045
Or even interesting.

768
00:58:24,214 --> 00:58:26,045
- What she's trying to say...
- Good night.

769
00:58:26,216 --> 00:58:27,649
Good night.

770
00:58:29,386 --> 00:58:30,512
Good night.

771
00:58:30,887 --> 00:58:33,583
Nigel, great day.
Gemma, sweet dreams.

772
00:58:40,230 --> 00:58:43,427
- Good night, sir.
- Good night, Tess.

773
00:58:48,138 --> 00:58:49,799
I hope...

774
00:58:51,007 --> 00:58:52,736
I hope, Gemma...

775
00:58:54,077 --> 00:58:58,035
...it hasn't been too dull for you here.

776
00:58:58,214 --> 00:59:01,741
Of course not, Daddy.
It's been really fun.

777
00:59:01,917 --> 00:59:03,578
Yes.

778
00:59:06,555 --> 00:59:08,045
Do you still play gin rummy?

779
00:59:08,224 --> 00:59:10,749
Oh, my God, all the time.
Whenever I fly.

780
00:59:11,827 --> 00:59:13,795
Oh. Penny a point?

781
00:59:34,950 --> 00:59:36,713
Hey, it's Tess.

782
00:59:36,886 --> 00:59:43,155
Don't get the wrong idea,
I just, uh, wanna talk. Um...

783
00:59:43,726 --> 00:59:49,665
I just thought,
since I've been kind of critical recently...

784
00:59:50,733 --> 00:59:55,193
...maybe I should tell you
how magnificent you were today...

785
00:59:55,371 --> 00:59:58,465
...you know, taking out their grid and...

786
00:59:59,808 --> 01:00:01,775
You couldn't hit Moe back.

787
01:00:02,176 --> 01:00:04,974
Uh, it just reminded me of how...

788
01:00:09,016 --> 01:00:10,779
Are you in here?

789
01:00:18,425 --> 01:00:19,551
Oh.

790
01:00:27,601 --> 01:00:29,068
Gin.

791
01:00:29,236 --> 01:00:30,931
What?

792
01:00:34,842 --> 01:00:36,810
Hundred and five.

793
01:00:36,977 --> 01:00:39,070
Twenty-eight thousand.

794
01:00:40,147 --> 01:00:43,981
- Dollars?
- Well, it's all going to charity, Daddy.

795
01:00:46,019 --> 01:00:48,351
Well, darling, I'm very pleased
you've inherited...

796
01:00:48,522 --> 01:00:51,423
<i>...not only your mother's beauty
and na:? Ve charm...</i>

797
01:00:53,327 --> 01:00:57,354
...but also her singular talent for
getting huge sums of money out of me...

798
01:00:57,531 --> 01:00:59,795
...with a modicum of effort.

799
01:01:04,705 --> 01:01:05,797
What's wrong?

800
01:01:08,307 --> 01:01:09,706
I don't want it.

801
01:01:09,876 --> 01:01:12,970
I'm sorry. It was a joke.

802
01:01:16,616 --> 01:01:18,709
I mean, be honest...

803
01:01:18,885 --> 01:01:23,379
...she didn't exactly marry me for love,
did she?

804
01:01:30,897 --> 01:01:33,024
My mother...

805
01:01:33,199 --> 01:01:38,364
...was a 24-year-old blackjack dealer
from Nebraska.

806
01:01:39,205 --> 01:01:43,437
You had to tip her $500
just to have a drink with you.

807
01:01:43,609 --> 01:01:47,136
You got married two weeks later
at the age of 175.

808
01:01:47,313 --> 01:01:49,008
- 51 to be precise.
- Now you're mad...

809
01:01:49,182 --> 01:01:52,413
...because she had the brains to get
some money before you dumped her?

810
01:01:52,585 --> 01:01:54,018
No, I'm mad about the amount.

811
01:01:54,187 --> 01:01:57,679
Oh, well, okay, you can have mine.
Because I'm cutting myself off.

812
01:01:57,857 --> 01:02:01,088
I don't want anything from you anymore.

813
01:02:01,861 --> 01:02:05,297
Except for food. And clothes.

814
01:02:06,098 --> 01:02:09,329
And rent and, like, travel.

815
01:02:09,502 --> 01:02:11,662
And I'm totally serious.

816
01:02:12,370 --> 01:02:18,434
Yes, that's what is so frightening
about it.

817
01:02:21,179 --> 01:02:22,840
Gemma?

818
01:02:27,018 --> 01:02:28,747
For what it's worth...

819
01:02:29,221 --> 01:02:32,679
...I loved your mother, and I love you.

820
01:03:17,735 --> 01:03:20,533
You believe in ghosts, Curtis?

821
01:03:21,505 --> 01:03:25,669
You know what,
you are some kind of stupid.

822
01:03:25,843 --> 01:03:28,334
Now you sound like my wife.

823
01:03:28,512 --> 01:03:29,809
Bunny around?

824
01:03:29,980 --> 01:03:34,508
You know, I can't hear you,
you talking to my deaf ear.

825
01:03:34,685 --> 01:03:36,448
Oh, sorry.

826
01:03:42,359 --> 01:03:43,417
Curtis?

827
01:03:58,309 --> 01:04:01,107
Take me to see Bigg Bunny.

828
01:04:01,278 --> 01:04:04,805
Bigg Bunny ain't never wanna find out
you didn't drown the first time.

829
01:04:06,150 --> 01:04:07,481
Okay.

830
01:04:09,353 --> 01:04:10,843
Shit.

831
01:04:13,257 --> 01:04:15,657
When's the last time
you had this thing sharpened?

832
01:04:16,860 --> 01:04:18,259
1715.

833
01:04:22,665 --> 01:04:24,462
Okay, okay, okay, one second.

834
01:04:24,867 --> 01:04:29,566
Now look, 20 people saw me today,
everybody on Moe's boat.

835
01:04:29,739 --> 01:04:32,367
Now if you guys take me to Bigg Bunny...

836
01:04:32,542 --> 01:04:36,638
...it's gonna look a lot better than if
he finds out I'm alive from someone else.

837
01:04:37,780 --> 01:04:41,511
- It ain't his decision no more.
- Now, who in the hell are you?

838
01:04:50,693 --> 01:04:52,354
Ow.

839
01:04:52,795 --> 01:04:55,389
Ain't no fool like a gold fool.

840
01:04:55,565 --> 01:04:57,760
Ain't that right, Mr. Finnegan?

841
01:04:59,268 --> 01:05:00,963
Who's the new guy?

842
01:05:01,838 --> 01:05:05,968
This here is Cyrus.
He's my new, uh, chief of staff.

843
01:05:07,043 --> 01:05:09,978
He's helping me to refocus, reform,
and renew.

844
01:05:10,680 --> 01:05:14,116
What do you need him for, huh?
We handling it.

845
01:05:18,354 --> 01:05:19,378
Whoa! Whoa, whoa!

846
01:05:19,555 --> 01:05:22,319
God, jeez. What's the...?

847
01:05:22,992 --> 01:05:24,391
Why'd you do that?

848
01:05:24,560 --> 01:05:26,322
Just a little restructure.

849
01:05:26,895 --> 01:05:31,059
See, you let this boy get past
you not just once, but twice.

850
01:05:31,233 --> 01:05:32,495
So I hope you focused now.

851
01:05:32,667 --> 01:05:35,431
Oh, extremely focused. Very motivated.

852
01:05:35,604 --> 01:05:39,438
My morale probably 20 percent higher
than when I came in here.

853
01:05:39,608 --> 01:05:41,803
- Can I get a word in?
- What? What do you want?

854
01:05:42,878 --> 01:05:45,176
I wanna buy some time.

855
01:05:46,248 --> 01:05:48,239
You still breathing, ain't you?

856
01:05:49,718 --> 01:05:51,151
Yeah, thank you.

857
01:05:51,720 --> 01:05:52,778
Now, hear me out.

858
01:05:53,855 --> 01:05:57,450
All right, the way I see it, you bet
on Moe, you got a fifty-fifty chance...

859
01:05:57,626 --> 01:06:02,120
...but you bet on the both of us, and we
cover twice the ground in half the time...

860
01:06:02,297 --> 01:06:07,735
...and I'm willing to give you 10 percent
of everything I find.

861
01:06:08,503 --> 01:06:11,438
Plus what I already owe you, of course.

862
01:06:12,274 --> 01:06:14,174
How much you say?

863
01:06:14,342 --> 01:06:16,936
Ten percent, across-the-board.

864
01:06:17,112 --> 01:06:18,477
Ten percent, huh?

865
01:06:18,814 --> 01:06:20,475
Wow.

866
01:06:21,283 --> 01:06:23,843
- Say it again.
- Come on, what...?

867
01:06:24,019 --> 01:06:25,418
You know, 12 percent's cool.

868
01:06:25,587 --> 01:06:28,181
You know, I couldn't even hear you.
What you say?

869
01:06:28,356 --> 01:06:31,381
- Fifteen percent, but I gotta find...
- I'm sorry, how much?

870
01:06:31,559 --> 01:06:34,528
- Eighteen, but I owe other people.
- That don't sound right.

871
01:06:34,695 --> 01:06:37,095
- Twenty percent, but that's it, final.
- Oh.

872
01:06:37,264 --> 01:06:39,095
Damn it. What? How much do you want?

873
01:06:39,967 --> 01:06:41,798
I'll tell you what.

874
01:06:45,840 --> 01:06:48,400
You find the treasure and I won't kill you.

875
01:07:06,126 --> 01:07:07,650
- How much do you owe him?
- Whoa.

876
01:07:08,729 --> 01:07:10,720
Jesus, Tess.

877
01:07:11,832 --> 01:07:12,958
How much do you owe him?

878
01:07:16,470 --> 01:07:19,439
Owe who? Owe who what?

879
01:07:19,840 --> 01:07:21,000
Bigg Bunny.

880
01:07:22,009 --> 01:07:23,476
I don't owe him any money.

881
01:07:23,644 --> 01:07:27,136
Finn, how much do you owe him?

882
01:07:27,715 --> 01:07:30,240
Just tell me so I'll know.

883
01:07:30,417 --> 01:07:33,818
Oh, God, Tess. I mean, that's so hard
to be specific about.

884
01:07:33,988 --> 01:07:36,455
- It's a really complex payment schedule...
- How much?

885
01:07:36,623 --> 01:07:41,287
Sixty-two thousand, five hundred and
eighty-one dollars and forty-three cents.

886
01:07:43,363 --> 01:07:44,625
But we're good now.

887
01:07:45,498 --> 01:07:47,830
Is there a reason
you didn't tell me this before?

888
01:07:49,035 --> 01:07:50,525
Yeah.

889
01:07:53,273 --> 01:07:55,036
You wouldn't have come.

890
01:07:56,776 --> 01:07:58,403
Yeah, I would.

891
01:07:59,913 --> 01:08:03,576
Just wouldn't have come with you.

892
01:08:13,526 --> 01:08:14,550
Are we finished?

893
01:08:18,631 --> 01:08:20,462
We sure are.

894
01:08:33,279 --> 01:08:34,473
- You good?
- Yeah.

895
01:08:34,647 --> 01:08:36,274
Okay.

896
01:08:37,250 --> 01:08:39,150
What happened to your face?

897
01:08:40,252 --> 01:08:42,686
Somebody hit me with a cricket bat.

898
01:08:42,888 --> 01:08:44,253
Ah.

899
01:08:46,425 --> 01:08:49,053
- This is a new type of regulator...
- Shove it up your ass.

900
01:08:49,227 --> 01:08:51,491
- All right, we're good to go.
- Ready, darling?

901
01:08:51,663 --> 01:08:53,528
Drop dead.

902
01:08:54,466 --> 01:08:56,957
This is just like the old days, huh?

903
01:09:28,333 --> 01:09:30,096
Hello, darling.

904
01:09:31,470 --> 01:09:32,994
Drink?

905
01:09:35,040 --> 01:09:36,371
I have one.

906
01:10:46,277 --> 01:10:48,108
You know what else
is really bugging me?

907
01:10:48,878 --> 01:10:50,243
No.

908
01:10:50,413 --> 01:10:54,645
Please, tell us. Because I may personally
drop dead from disappointment...

909
01:10:54,818 --> 01:10:59,016
...if I don't find out the 700-millionth thing
about life on planet Earth...

910
01:10:59,189 --> 01:11:00,850
...that is bugging you.

911
01:11:01,424 --> 01:11:02,789
Well, this is fun.

912
01:11:02,959 --> 01:11:04,392
No, listen.

913
01:11:05,028 --> 01:11:08,589
If I am the Dutch frigate
stuck on a reef in a dead calm...

914
01:11:08,765 --> 01:11:11,825
<i>...in the same cove
the Aurelia sank three years earlier...</i>

915
01:11:12,001 --> 01:11:16,199
...in less than 30 feet
of the clearest water in the world...

916
01:11:17,107 --> 01:11:20,975
Then how come I can't see her?

917
01:11:25,148 --> 01:11:27,173
Because she isn't there.

918
01:11:29,619 --> 01:11:30,745
Yeah, I don't know.

919
01:11:30,920 --> 01:11:34,879
No, no, no. Sebastian specifically said
that's where she sank.

920
01:11:35,058 --> 01:11:36,889
- And he said it.
- Yeah.

921
01:11:37,060 --> 01:11:41,326
My dear children, your entire theory
is predicated on the proposition...

922
01:11:41,498 --> 01:11:46,265
...that Sebastian lied about everything he
could to prevent the ship being found.

923
01:11:46,436 --> 01:11:50,566
So why on Earth would
he tell the truth about where she sank?

924
01:11:51,574 --> 01:11:54,770
<i>I mean, it seems to me that
the Aurelia can't be in the cove...</i>

925
01:11:54,943 --> 01:11:58,379
...for the simple reason that
that's where Sebastian said she was.

926
01:12:13,862 --> 01:12:14,988
Sorry to disturb.

927
01:12:15,164 --> 01:12:17,860
We've had to move to the lee side
on account of the storm.

928
01:12:18,033 --> 01:12:20,058
She won't fit in the marina?

929
01:12:20,235 --> 01:12:23,864
Afraid not. A taxi will take you
to the beach on the north end.

930
01:12:24,039 --> 01:12:27,031
- Call, we'll pick you up on the launch.
- Better safe than sorry.

931
01:12:27,209 --> 01:12:28,642
Sir.

932
01:12:29,344 --> 01:12:32,245
I've grown rather fond of not sinking.

933
01:12:32,447 --> 01:12:34,472
Ugh. Don't even say that.

934
01:12:34,650 --> 01:12:37,585
Oh, it would be a shame
to lose the art collection.

935
01:12:37,920 --> 01:12:38,944
Or Gemma's shoes.

936
01:12:39,855 --> 01:12:43,484
Especially because we're so close
to shore, you know?

937
01:12:47,329 --> 01:12:48,421
Oh, my God.

938
01:12:50,332 --> 01:12:51,799
What?

939
01:12:52,201 --> 01:12:53,429
Oh, my God, of course.

940
01:12:53,602 --> 01:12:55,263
Of course what?

941
01:12:57,472 --> 01:12:59,996
You are a genius.

942
01:13:01,843 --> 01:13:03,003
Stefan.

943
01:13:03,444 --> 01:13:05,537
- Stefan.
- Yes.

944
01:13:05,880 --> 01:13:08,474
Why did you pick the north beach?

945
01:13:08,983 --> 01:13:12,111
I didn't. It's the only beach on the
island not blocked by the reef.

946
01:13:12,887 --> 01:13:16,015
Yes. Yes. He ran her aground.

947
01:13:16,190 --> 01:13:17,851
What are you so happy about?

948
01:13:18,025 --> 01:13:20,550
- He ran her aground.
- What?

949
01:13:20,728 --> 01:13:26,428
To save the Dowry. Sebastian ran
the whole goddamn thing aground.

950
01:13:27,735 --> 01:13:31,193
Bet you $ 1000 I find something
between here and that beach.

951
01:13:31,372 --> 01:13:33,101
You don't have $ 1000.

952
01:13:33,841 --> 01:13:34,933
Fine, make it 10.

953
01:13:35,509 --> 01:13:36,976
You don't have $ 10.

954
01:13:37,745 --> 01:13:39,804
Fine, make it a million.

955
01:13:46,053 --> 01:13:47,611
What are you doing?

956
01:13:47,788 --> 01:13:50,621
You think I'm letting you go out
there alone, you're crazy.

957
01:13:50,958 --> 01:13:52,448
What, you don't trust me?

958
01:13:52,627 --> 01:13:55,187
Why on Earth would I trust you?

959
01:13:56,697 --> 01:13:58,221
Huh.

960
01:15:15,541 --> 01:15:17,406
- I found a cannon.
- I found a cannon.

961
01:15:17,576 --> 01:15:19,237
- You did what?
- You mean there's two?

962
01:15:19,411 --> 01:15:20,901
- There's two cannons.
- Aah!

963
01:15:21,080 --> 01:15:23,947
- And I owe you a million dollars. Aah!
- Yes, you do. Oh!

964
01:15:24,116 --> 01:15:25,549
Whoo!

965
01:15:25,985 --> 01:15:27,816
<i>We got the Aurelia, baby!</i>

966
01:15:27,987 --> 01:15:32,481
Listen to me, if anybody finds out about
this outside of our crew, we are screwed.

967
01:15:32,658 --> 01:15:35,252
Wow. Can't you just enjoy this
for a second?

968
01:15:36,495 --> 01:15:38,520
Oh, I'm enjoying it.

969
01:15:42,401 --> 01:15:45,564
Oh, God. Thank God.

970
01:15:49,208 --> 01:15:51,642
Whoo-hoo!

971
01:16:18,870 --> 01:16:20,167
Well, there's not much here.

972
01:16:20,338 --> 01:16:24,274
Now, they probably burned the ship
and took everything inland.

973
01:16:24,442 --> 01:16:27,900
Look, a pistol.
Cool.

974
01:16:28,079 --> 01:16:31,412
All right, well, what do we know
about Topsail Cay?

975
01:16:31,816 --> 01:16:34,148
We got the town, the church...

976
01:16:34,318 --> 01:16:35,444
There's Preacher's Cave.

977
01:16:35,620 --> 01:16:38,646
We were up there once.
It said something about first settlers...

978
01:16:38,823 --> 01:16:39,847
...religious freedom...

979
01:16:40,024 --> 01:16:42,549
God, I think that is just so important.

980
01:16:44,262 --> 01:16:45,559
Yeah, but that was like...

981
01:16:46,464 --> 01:16:49,956
- Oh.
- Like 1780-something.

982
01:16:51,102 --> 01:16:54,367
I mean, Sebastian beat them here
by almost 70 years.

983
01:16:54,539 --> 01:16:56,734
If there are any records,
they're in the church.

984
01:16:56,908 --> 01:17:00,139
- Letters, journals, sermons.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

985
01:17:01,479 --> 01:17:03,606
That's smart, Tess.

